[[File:Shinmon of Wakamiya-hachimangu (Hitachiota).jpg|thumb|right|245px|Shinmon (gate)]]

'''Wakamiya Hachimangū''' (若宮八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Hitachiōta|ja|常陸太田市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県|12=draft|12=draft}}, Japan. The shrine's rank under the {{ill|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft|12=draft}} was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== History ==
The shrine was established during the {{ill|Ōei era|ja|応永|12=draft|12=draft}} (circa 1400) by {{ill|Yoshihito Satake|ja|佐竹義人|12=draft|12=draft}}, who invited its deity from {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|ja|鶴岡八幡宮|12=draft|12=draft}} in {{ill|Kamakura|ja|鎌倉市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was originally enshrined within {{ill|Ōta Castle (Hitachi Province)|ja|太田城 (常陸国)|12=draft|12=draft}} as a guardian deity and served as the prayer site for the {{ill|Satake clan|ja|佐竹氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.

Research suggests that the Satake clan initially revered a {{ill|Hachiman shrine|ja|八幡社|12=draft|12=draft}} derived from {{ill|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|ja|石清水八幡宮|12=draft|12=draft}}, which was the guardian shrine of the Minamoto clan in Hitachi. However, Yoshihito Satake, who had ties with the {{ill|Uesugi clan|ja|上杉氏|12=draft|12=draft}}, instead adopted the enshrinement of Tsurugaoka Hachimangū, possibly against opposition from the Satake family.<ref>Teiko Tsutsumi, "Satake Clan and Hachiman Worship," {{ill|Ibaraki Prefectural History Museum Bulletin|ja|茨城県立歴史館報|12=draft|12=draft}} No. 28, 2001. Compiled in {{ill|Research Series on Medieval Kanto Warriors Vol. 30: Hitachi Satake Clan|ja|シリーズ・中世関東武士の研究 第三十巻 常陸佐竹氏|12=draft|12=draft}} (Kōshōshō Publishing, 2021), pp. 192–227.</ref>

Although the Satake clan was later relocated to {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田|12=draft|12=draft}} after the {{ill|Battle of Sekigahara|ja|関ヶ原の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}}, they took the shrine's deity with them to {{ill|Ōdate Castle|ja|大館城|12=draft|12=draft}} as its guardian spirit. The deity was subsequently enshrined at {{ill|Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|ja|大館八幡神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, continuing its role as a protector.<ref name=jinjacho>{{Cite web|title=八幡神社 |url=http://akita-jinjacho.sakura.ne.jp/tatsujin_etc/kennsaku/oodate/67_hachiman_hachiman.html |publisher=Akita Prefecture Shrine Association |accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>

In {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|12=draft|12=draft}} 14 (1609), the first {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Mito Domain|ja|水戸藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yorifusa|ja|徳川頼房|12=draft|12=draft}}, was healed of an illness after praying at the shrine. Thereafter, the {{ill|Mito Tokugawa clan|ja|水戸徳川家|12=draft|12=draft}} held the shrine in high reverence. In {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1692), the second daimyō, {{ill|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|ja|徳川光圀|12=draft|12=draft}} (popularly known as Mito Kōmon), designated the shrine as a guardian of the Ōta district.

In {{ill|Hōei|ja|宝永|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1708), the shrine was relocated to its current location alongside the {{ill|Ōta Inari Shrine|ja|太田稲荷神社|12=draft|12=draft}}, which had been worshiped together with it.

In 1940 (Showa 15), based on the tradition that a woman named Tsuruko accompanied the deity’s transfer from Tsurugaoka Hachimangū and oversaw its rituals, the shrine's parishioner priestesses revived the "Tsuruko Dance." Recently, this {{ill|kagura|ja|神楽|12=draft|12=draft}} offering has been expanded to include performances such as {{ill|Urayasu no Mai|ja|浦安の舞|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Toyo no Sakai no Mai|ja|豊栄の舞|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Yaotome no Mai|ja|八乙女舞|12=draft|12=draft}}, which are performed with grace during major festivals.
[[File:Kaguraden of Wakamiya-hachimangu (Hitachiota).jpg|thumb|right|245px|Kaguraden]]

== Enshrined Deities ==
* '''[[Ōsasagi no Mikoto]]''' (Emperor Nintoku)
* '''[[Ukanomitama no Mikoto]]'''

== Festivals ==
* January: {{ill|Saitan-sai|ja|元旦祭|Saitan-sai=Saitan-sai|lt=Saitan-sai (New Year's Festival)|12=draft|12=draft}}
* February: {{ill|Setsubun|ja|節分追儺祭|lt=Setsubun Tsuina-sai|12=draft|12=draft}}
* May: festival
* June: {{ill|Nagoshi no Harae|ja|夏越の祓|12=draft|12=draft}}
* September: Autumn Festival
* December: {{ill|Ōharae|ja|大祓|12=draft|12=draft}}

== Cultural Properties ==
* Large {{ill|zelkova|ja|ケヤキ|12=draft|12=draft}} tree (designated a natural monument of Ibaraki Prefecture)
* Hanging scroll of Hachiman as a monk
* Stone sword artifacts
* Military fan (attributed to {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshimitsu|ja|源義光|12=draft|12=draft}})

== Auxiliary Shrines ==
* {{ill|Kitano Tenjin Shrine|ja|北野天神社|12=draft|12=draft}} (Plum Tenjin) – Established in {{ill|Kōhei 6|ja|康平|12=draft|12=draft}} (1062) by {{ill|Minamoto no Yoshiie|ja|源義家|12=draft|12=draft}} to pray for victory in the {{ill|Earlier Nine Years' War|ja|前九年の役|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* {{ill|Ichihime Shrine|ja|市比売神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Ashio Shrine|ja|足尾神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Atago Shrine|ja|愛宕神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Wakazumi Shrine|ja|別雷神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Fuji Shrine|ja|富士神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
* {{ill|Awashima Shrine|ja|淡島神社|12=draft|12=draft}}
<gallery mode="packed" widths="150px" heights="160px">
File:Ota-tenmangu in Wakamiya-hachimanhu (Hitachiota).jpg|Kitano Tenjin Shrine
File:Keidaisha1 in Wakamiya-hachimangu (Hitachiota).jpg|Ichihime Shrine, Wakazumi Shrine, Atago Shrine
File:Ashio-jinja in Wakamiya-hachimangu (Hitachiota).jpg|Ashio Shrine
File:Fuji-jinja in Wakamiya-hachimangu (Hitachiota).jpg|Fuji Shrine
</gallery>

== Access ==
The shrine is approximately 1.5 km north of {{ill|Hitachi-Ōta Station|ja|常陸太田駅|12=draft|12=draft}} on the {{ill|East Japan Railway Company|ja|東日本旅客鉄道|12=draft|12=draft}} (JR). It is a 20-minute walk.

