In {{ill|Keichō|ja|慶長|12=draft|12=draft}} 14 (1609), the first {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Mito Domain|ja|水戸藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yorifusa|ja|徳川頼房|12=draft|12=draft}}, was healed of an illness after praying at the shrine. Thereafter, the {{ill|Mito Tokugawa clan|ja|水戸徳川家|12=draft|12=draft}} held the shrine in high reverence. In {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|12=draft|12=draft}} 5 (1692), the second daimyō, {{ill|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|ja|徳川光圀|12=draft|12=draft}} (popularly known as Mito Kōmon), designated the shrine as a guardian of the Ōta district.

