In 1940 (Showa 15), based on the tradition that a woman named Tsuruko accompanied the deity’s transfer from Tsurugaoka Hachimangū and oversaw its rituals, the shrine's parishioner priestesses revived the "Tsuruko Dance." Recently, this {{ill|kagura|ja|神楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}} offering has been expanded to include performances such as {{ill|Urayasu no Mai|ja|浦安の舞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Toyo no Sakai no Mai|ja|豊栄の舞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Yaotome no Mai|ja|八乙女舞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which are performed with grace during major festivals.
