'''Wakamiya Hachimangū''' (若宮八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in {{ill|Hitachiōta|ja|常陸太田市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hitachiōta|qq=}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|ja|茨城県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ibaraki Prefecture|qq=}}, Japan. The shrine's Rank under the {{ill|Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|13=User:Immanuelle/Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|qq=}} was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|qq=}}.

== History ==
The shrine was established during the {{ill|Ōei era|ja|応永|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōei era|qq=}} (circa 1400) by {{ill|Yoshihito Satake|ja|佐竹義人|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshihito Satake|qq=}}, who invited its deity from {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|ja|鶴岡八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|qq=}} in {{ill|Kamakura|ja|鎌倉市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura|qq=}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|ja|神奈川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kanagawa Prefecture|qq=}}. It was originally enshrined within {{ill|Ōta Castle (Hitachi Province)|ja|太田城 (常陸国)|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta Castle (Hitachi Province)|qq=}} as a guardian deity and served as the prayer site for the {{ill|Satake clan|ja|佐竹氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Satake clan|qq=}}.

Research suggests that the Satake clan initially revered a {{ill|Hachiman shrine|lt=Hachiman shrine|lt=Hachiman Shrine|ja|八幡社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman shrine|qq=}} derived from {{ill|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|ja|石清水八幡宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Iwashimizu Hachimangū|qq=}}, which was the guardian shrine of the Minamoto clan in Hitachi. However, Yoshihito Satake, who had ties with the {{ill|Uesugi clan|ja|上杉氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Uesugi clan|qq=}}, instead adopted the enshrinement of Tsurugaoka Hachimangū, possibly against opposition from the Satake family.<ref>Teiko Tsutsumi, "Satake Clan and Hachiman Worship," {{ill|Ibaraki Prefectural History Museum Bulletin|ja|茨城県立歴史館報|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ibaraki Prefectural History Museum Bulletin|qq=}} No. 28, 2001. Compiled in {{ill|Research Series on Medieval Kanto Warriors Vol. 30: Hitachi Satake Clan|ja|シリーズ・中世関東武士の研究 第三十巻 常陸佐竹氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Research Series on Medieval Kanto Warriors Vol. 30: Hitachi Satake Clan|qq=}} (Kōshōshō Publishing, 2021), pp. 192–227.</ref>

Although the Satake clan was later relocated to {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akita|qq=}} after the {{ill|Battle of Sekigahara|ja|関ヶ原の戦い|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Battle of Sekigahara|qq=}}, they took the shrine's deity with them to {{ill|Ōdate Castle|ja|大館城|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōdate Castle|qq=}} as its guardian spirit. The deity was subsequently enshrined at {{ill|Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|ja|大館八幡神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|qq=}}, continuing its role as a protector.<ref name=jinjacho>{{Cite web|title=八幡神社 |url=http://akita-jinjacho.sakura.ne.jp/tatsujin_etc/kennsaku/oodate/67_hachiman_hachiman.html |publisher=Akita Prefecture Shrine Association |accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>

In {{ill|Keichō|1=Keichō|2=ja|3=慶長|ja|慶長|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Keichō|qq=}} 14 (1609), the first {{ill|daimyō|ja|大名|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/daimyō|qq=}} of the {{ill|Mito Domain|ja|水戸藩|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mito Domain|qq=}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yorifusa|ja|徳川頼房|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Yorifusa|qq=}}, was healed of an illness after praying at the shrine. Thereafter, the {{ill|Mito Tokugawa clan|ja|水戸徳川家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Mito Tokugawa clan|qq=}} held the shrine in high reverence. In {{ill|Genroku|ja|元禄|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Genroku|qq=}} 5 (1692), the second daimyō, {{ill|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|ja|徳川光圀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tokugawa Mitsukuni|qq=}} (popularly known as Mito Kōmon), designated the shrine as a guardian of the Ōta district.

In {{ill|Hōei|ja|宝永|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hōei|qq=}} 5 (1708), the shrine was relocated to its current location alongside the {{ill|Ōta Inari Shrine|ja|太田稲荷神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta Inari Shrine|qq=}}, which had been worshiped together with it.

In 1940 (Showa 15), based on the tradition that a woman named Tsuruko accompanied the deity’s transfer from Tsurugaoka Hachimangū and oversaw its rituals, the shrine's parishioner priestesses revived the "Tsuruko Dance." Recently, this {{ill|kagura|ja|神楽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/kagura|qq=}} offering has been expanded to include performances such as {{ill|Urayasu no Mai|ja|浦安の舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Urayasu no Mai|qq=}}, {{ill|Toyo no Sakai no Mai|ja|豊栄の舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyo no Sakai no Mai|qq=}}, and {{ill|Yaotome no Mai|ja|八乙女舞|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yaotome no Mai|qq=}}, which are performed with grace during major festivals.
