'''Wakamiya Hachimangū''' (若宮八幡宮) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|Hitachiōta, Ibaraki|en|Hitachiōta, Ibaraki|WD=Q838663|lt=Hitachiōta|1=Hitachiōta, Ibaraki}}, {{ill|Ibaraki Prefecture|en|Ibaraki Prefecture|WD=Q83273|lt=Ibaraki Prefecture|1=Ibaraki Prefecture}}, Japan. The shrine's Rank under the {{ill|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|en|Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|WD=Q712534|lt=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} was {{ill|Gōsha|ja|郷社|1=Gō-sha|WD=Q134917316}}{{efn|District Shrines|WD=Q90139226|lt=Ken-sha|1=modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gōsha|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 近代社格制度|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q712534}}.

== History ==
The shrine was established during the {{ill|Ōei|en|Ōei|WD=Q1193078|lt=Ōei era|1=Ōei}} (circa 1400) by {{ill|Yoshihito Satake|ja|佐竹義人|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshihito Satake|1=Satake Yoshihito|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11383421}}, who invited its deity from {{ill|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|en|Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|WD=Q701403|lt=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū|1=Tsurugaoka Hachimangū}} in {{ill|Kamakura|en|Kamakura|WD=Q200267|lt=Kamakura|1=Kamakura}}, {{ill|Kanagawa Prefecture|en|Kanagawa Prefecture|WD=Q127513|lt=Kanagawa Prefecture|1=Kanagawa Prefecture}}. It was originally enshrined within {{ill|Ōta Castle (Hitachi Province)|ja|太田城 (常陸国)|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta Castle (Hitachi Province)|1=Ōda Castle|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q5369726}} as a guardian deity and served as the prayer site for the {{ill|Satake clan|en|Satake clan|WD=Q2975363|lt=Satake clan|1=Satake clan}}.

Research suggests that the Satake clan initially revered a {{ill|Hachiman shrine|lt=Hachiman shrine|lt=Hachiman Shrine|ja|八幡社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hachiman shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 八幡宮}} derived from {{ill|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|en|Iwashimizu Hachimangū|WD=Q710098|lt=Iwashimizu Hachimangū|1=Iwashimizu Hachimangū}}, which was the guardian shrine of the Minamoto clan in Hitachi. However, Yoshihito Satake, who had ties with the {{ill|Uesugi clan|en|Uesugi clan|WD=Q1150058|lt=Uesugi clan|1=Uesugi clan}}, instead adopted the enshrinement of Tsurugaoka Hachimangū, possibly against opposition from the Satake family.<ref>Teiko Tsutsumi, "Satake Clan and Hachiman Worship," {{ill|Ibaraki Prefectural History Museum Bulletin|ja|茨城県立歴史館報|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ibaraki Prefectural History Museum Bulletin|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} No. 28, 2001. Compiled in {{ill|Research Series on Medieval Kanto Warriors Vol. 30: Hitachi Satake Clan|ja|シリーズ・中世関東武士の研究 第三十巻 常陸佐竹氏|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Research Series on Medieval Kanto Warriors Vol. 30: Hitachi Satake Clan|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Kōshōshō Publishing, 2021), pp. 192–227.</ref>

Although the Satake clan was later relocated to {{ill|Akita|ja|秋田|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Akita|1=Q11256953|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11256953}} after the {{ill|Battle of Sekigahara|en|Battle of Sekigahara|WD=Q234188|lt=Battle of Sekigahara|1=Battle of Sekigahara}}, they took the shrine's deity with them to {{ill|Ōdate Castle|ja|大館城|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōdate Castle|1=Ōdate Castle|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11441913}} as its guardian spirit. The deity was subsequently enshrined at {{ill|Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|ja|大館八幡神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|1=Ōdate Hachiman Shrine|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q21606446}}, continuing its role as a protector.<ref name=jinjacho>{{Cite web|title=八幡神社 |url=http://akita-jinjacho.sakura.ne.jp/tatsujin_etc/kennsaku/oodate/67_hachiman_hachiman.html |publisher=Akita Prefecture Shrine Association |accessdate=2015-10-12}}</ref>

In {{ill|Keichō|en|Keichō|WD=Q1328185|lt=Keichō|1=Keichō}} 14 (1609), the first {{ill|Daimyo|en|Daimyo|WD=Q61982|lt=daimyō|1=Daimyo}} of the {{ill|Mito Domain|en|Mito Domain|WD=Q1146904|lt=Mito Domain|1=Mito Domain}}, {{ill|Tokugawa Yorifusa|en|Tokugawa Yorifusa|WD=Q1133680|lt=Tokugawa Yorifusa|1=Tokugawa Yorifusa}}, was healed of an illness after praying at the shrine. Thereafter, the {{ill|Mito Tokugawa family|en|Mito Tokugawa family|WD=Q842246|lt=Mito Tokugawa clan|1=Mito Tokugawa family}} held the shrine in high reverence. In {{ill|Genroku|en|Genroku|WD=Q1325001|lt=Genroku|1=Genroku}} 5 (1692), the second daimyō, {{ill|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|en|Tokugawa Mitsukuni|WD=Q1194944|lt=Tokugawa Mitsukuni|1=Tokugawa Mitsukuni}} (popularly known as Mito Kōmon), designated the shrine as a guardian of the Ōta district.

In {{ill|Hōei|en|Hōei|WD=Q1145262|lt=Hōei|1=Hōei}} 5 (1708), the shrine was relocated to its current location alongside the {{ill|Ōta Inari Shrine|ja|太田稲荷神社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōta Inari Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, which had been worshiped together with it.

In 1940 (Showa 15), based on the tradition that a woman named Tsuruko accompanied the deity’s transfer from Tsurugaoka Hachimangū and oversaw its rituals, the shrine's parishioner priestesses revived the "Tsuruko Dance." Recently, this {{ill|Kagura|en|Kagura|WD=Q1348260|lt=kagura|1=Kagura}} offering has been expanded to include performances such as {{ill|Urayasu no Mai|ja|浦安の舞|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Urayasu no Mai|1=Urayasu no mai|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11558194}}, {{ill|Toyo no Sakai no Mai|ja|豊栄の舞|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyo no Sakai no Mai|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, and {{ill|Yaotome no Mai|ja|八乙女舞|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yaotome no Mai|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 巫女舞|1=miko mai|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11479841}}, which are performed with grace during major festivals.
